Mechelen van Aken
In antwoort aenden ue van 24 deser seynde ue met de
wagens eene pack, daer inde 2 superf ijne swerte volgens
facture aenden voet deser, hadt ick ue die niet volgeseyt,
ick soude heden voor contant gelt die tot beteren goryge
vercoght hebben syn gisteren laet eerst aencomen ul
moet de maete rekeninge op hollants & met eene elle
th sich vergenoegen vallen die corter, soo moet gij den
prijs vanden incoop beswaeren, want ick daer niet anders
mach aen Missen & gelyck alle hollants goet vercoght
wort uytterlyck met een elle t lakens volgens ue stael synder
geen oock geene apparentie wanneer het verschgeet sal
come bly heb den bode niet vernomm ingeslote
hoeh 2 staelen van fijne breet die naestaen ue come
Londen Wall & Will kent
sence my last of 24 cur red yours of 8 & 12 d god send
the ships from london well over no news yett of them
manney capers are att sea & do much damage a same
for boath nation not to hinder such thing, which is
so easeley to be don, I hope your ostendish convoy
soone with you to seth the ships now in loadinge &
though you make no mention of the northrens so often
writt of yett I question not butt they shall come
p this first, or elce you might as well pre mij pacquett
therefore send what cause white or half, or as manney as you
can have besides of the last orders & if the rest te
to deare & not to be had to content send the 3 of £10:3:
in some pack or other & make up all what you can for this
convoy, so flannels pack white & & what I ordered for
hull is to be shipped for holland p first departing
convoy rather for Amst then that dans Rott my
packes from leed all with 3 white baeyes, from London
with cottons of 20 a 21 pence a good as soon as I see the patt
of the span clothes shall order more as for shipping 2 packes in
Colhthurst your there was non others butt full, had you leffout
one as least yeare you did with N73 then one had been saved, &
you must doe as is ordered, & do ill, then can not be replyed,
will not have shipped att hull above one pack of cloth in a ship &
writt so more often, 2 packes of bayes migh do when you can not other
wite I rest
onder Richard Southell
28 meirt 1695
In answer to yours of 12 cur I should be were glad in case the
northrens could be gett reddy for this convoy where in you could
doe mee a service, desireing you to endeavour also for all the
rest I ordered to come for this convoy, & if anney span clothes
be wanting forward what is reddy, & if non to be found so low
prises to N 7: 10 & 12 doe as best you can though 6 pence
more a yeard if butt a liveley cullour & good cloth & some grayes
to the patt sent 24 cur to which referre you, so what you
finde not to full content buy not & send no more then what is
intirely good loveley lists & liveley cullours & well pressed,
I have severall sp clothes of yours yett remaining for beeng
so dead cullours lile bayes no strenght in the cloth nor press
n kent are in sp clothes the best, therefore pray doe that
mee might in lange wish you if you can have 5 EE yall
more
=ow marcks with this convoy then buy them att prise
curtt if white without streep or spots fitt for religious
habids, I have red a letter from m collier belong seas
4 cur dated youghall 7 gb 94 & an inclssed to Cape
henry Collier att S Germaine or elce where in france, I know
not how to forward that safeley yett I'll doe what I
can to inquie ofer him inclosed & answer to our old freind
which please to send him, I have remitted monney to Amst to
have bills there for londen, because exa is falling, so besare
I shall remitt you timely the needfull whilst I rest
as for ensuring seene you will not doe itt your self I hall doe hee
what I shall thinck fist give butt timely advise
